√©vu √† cet effet et joignez de pr√©f√©rence un extrait ou l\'int√©gralit√© du document √† traduire. Indiquez √©galement la date √† laquelle vous souhaiteriez que ce travail vous soit remis.\r\n\r\nVeuillez noter qu\'en passant commande pour une traduction, vous reconnaissez avoir pris connaissance des <a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/traduction-conditions-de-service/\" target=\"_blank\">conditions de service</a> et y adh√©rer sans r√©serve.\r\n\r\n[contact-form-7 id=\"58\" title=\"Formulaire de contact 1\"]','Traduction','','inherit','open','open','','87-revision-v1','','','2015-01-15 10:44:18','2015-01-15 09:44:18','',87,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/87-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(374,1,'2015-01-15 10:47:36','2015-01-15 09:47:36','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won‚Äôt listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be useful if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won‚Äôt prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won‚Äôt learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I‚Äôm planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That‚Äôs how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence‚Ä¶\r\n\r\nI‚Äôm not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because-let‚Äôs be realistic- most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you‚Äôre able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you‚Äôll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-159 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you‚Äôre a total beginner and don‚Äôt understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that‚Äôs the great news : you don‚Äôt even have to understand what you‚Äôre listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you‚Äôre beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you‚Äôre perfectly fluent in). You shouldn‚Äôt of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you‚Äôre interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc‚Ä¶\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I‚Äôll introduce you to some of France‚Äôs most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bient√¥t !','Here is my first learning advice to you','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2015-01-15 10:47:36','2015-01-15 09:47:36','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/158-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(375,1,'2015-01-20 18:42:54','2015-01-20 17:42:54','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/images.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-384\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/images-150x150.png\" alt=\"images\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIn my last post, I recommended you listen to French as often as possible and I hope you‚Äôve followed my advice and found out how efficient it can be.\r\n\r\nFor those of you who are uninspired or simply not very familiar with French cinema, here is a list of movies you might like. As we‚Äôve just entered 2015, I thought I would pay a kind of tribute to the past year by only selecting some of 2014‚Äôs most popular French films. I haven‚Äôt seen them all but I tried to pick movies that tackle some typical aspects of French culture so you can learn a bit more about France while learning the language.\r\n\r\nAll those movies except one have been rated ¬´ suitable for all audiences ¬ª but I have to warn you that France is very liberal when it comes to depictions of sex and light violence or coarse language so some of them might still feature scenes or jokes that can be considered disturbing or offensive in other cultures. If you intend on watching those with children or teenagers you should probably check how they‚Äôve been rated in your own country.\r\n\r\nDans mon dernier article, je vous ai recommand√© d‚Äô√©couter du fran√ßais aussi souvent que possible et j‚Äôesp√®re que vous avez suivi mon conseil et constat√© √† quel point cela est efficace.\r\n\r\nPour ceux d‚Äôentre vous qui sont en 