arted the celebration of April fool‚Äôs day, references can be found as soon as the 1500‚Äôs but these accounts are infrequent and not very detailed.\r\n\r\nThe most popular theory is that it began around 1582 in France during the reformation of the calendar. Before France adopted the Gregorian calendar, they celebrated New Year‚Äôs for 8 days, beginning on March 25th and ending on April 1st.When they switched calendar system, the 8 days moved from April 1st to January 1st.\r\n\r\nBecause they didn‚Äôt have internet, phones, social media and a mail system, all the people didn‚Äôt hear about this change until years later. Those who didn‚Äôt hear about the change continued to celebrate New Year‚Äôs in April; others refused to celebrate out of rebellion. Those who had been informed of the change and adjusted their calendar began to make fun of these fools who hadn‚Äôt been informed or rebellious. This harassment evolved into the tradition of playing pranks on the first day of April (and then spread to other countries).\r\n\r\nHowever April fool‚Äôs day was already established in England which didn‚Äôt switch calendar system until 1752. Also people were already engaging in pranks and light-heartedness around this time of the year long before the French switched their calendar system such as in the case of the ancient roman festival of Hileria.\r\n\r\nModern celebrations of April‚Äôs fool‚Äôs day have slightly different traditions (depending on the country you‚Äôre in) but they all have a similar theme of pranking or humiliating individuals.\r\nIn France, they try to tape an image of a fish in your back without you noticing and in Portugal they throw flour at you. In England, you‚Äôre only supposed to pull jokes until noon and if you pull a joke after noon you‚Äôre called an April‚Äôs fool.\r\nIn United States and Britain even popular media outlets and companies have been known to get involved in the fun. In 1996 Taco Bell announced that it had purchased the liberty bell