55','2015-05-06 09:28:55','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_476\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"235\"]<a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/675px-Convallaria_majalis_0002.jpg\"><img class=\"  wp-image-476\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/675px-Convallaria_majalis_0002-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"675px-Convallaria_majalis_0002\" width=\"235\" height=\"235\" /></a> <a title=\"&quot;Convallaria majalis 0002&quot; by H. Zell - Own work. Licensed under CC BY-SA 3.0 via Wikimedia Commons -\" href=\"http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Convallaria_majalis_0002.JPG#/media/File:Convallaria_majalis_0002.JPG\" target=\"_blank\">H.Zell</a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Labor Day in France</strong>\r\n\r\nMay 1 is Labor Day or International Workers‚Äô Day in many countries around the globe. In France, May 1 is called La f√™te du Travail or 1er mai. It‚Äôs celebrated with demonstrations and parades organized by workers‚Äô organizations and trade unions aimed at airing the demands of workers and campaigning for their rights.These events can also be used to emphasize present social issues, to fight racism or to campaign for the rights of everyone in general.\r\nAs it‚Äôs a public holiday in France, most shops, stores, post offices, banks and businesses are closed on F√™te du Travail.\r\n\r\n<strong>History of 1er mai</strong>\r\n\r\nFrance officially introduced the 8-hour working holiday on April 23, 1919. May 1 became the Labor Day in France. It was called International Worker\'s Day (F√™te internationale des Travailleurs)¬†during that time. This was later changed into Work and Social Unity Day (F√™te du Travail et de la Concorde sociale)¬†during World War II by the Vichy regime. There was no holiday on May 1st between 1944 and 1947. It was officially named Labor Day (La F√™te du Travail) on the 29th of April 1948.\r\n\r\n<strong>Public Life</strong>\r\n\r\nOutside of tourist spots every cafes, restaurants, banks, stores, post offices and businesses are closed. Railway stations, major highways, airports and some stores in Paris or big cities, however, may be open. Schedules of public transport service differ depending on where people want to travel or where they live. Demonstrations and parades may cause traffic disruptions in the centers of huge cities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Tradition of Giving Lilies of the Valley to Loved Ones</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople give bouquets of dog rose flowers or lily-of-the-valley to loved ones. In French lily-of-the-valley is muguet.Families with kids in country areas wake up early and go into the forest to pick the flowers. Lilies of the valley are in full bloom in late April and early May. It‚Äôs among those wild plants that grow very quickly, invading edges of wood and clearings. You only need to be patient in picking it and making small bouquets.\r\n\r\nGiving lilies of the valley comes from an ancient pagan tradition where people adorn themselves with flowers to celebrate spring. Many provinces have maintained a version of this ancient tradition by decorating a pole with flowers. This is a reminder of the tradition of planting flowering trees outside the door of the females to marry off. A feast that celebrates love, spring and nature then follows this.\r\n\r\nLabor organizations and individuals in metropolitan areas sell bouquets of the flowers on the street on May 1. There are some rules that allow some organizations and people to sell these flowers on the day without adhering to retail guidelines or paying tax.\r\n\r\n<strong>When did the tradition start?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe French tradition of giving a bouquet of lilies of the valley as a good luck charm originates from the 1st of May 1561 when King Charles IX was presented with one. He liked it and decided to give lilies of the valley to his court ladies every year on May 1.\r\n\r\nAround 1900, men began to give bouquet of lilies of the valley to women to show their affection. T